The book centers on questions of Native nation-building and international diplomacy, and it argues that Native American migration and practices of offering refuge to migrants in crisis enabled Native nations to survive the violence of colonization.Indeed, these practices also made them powerful. When European settlers began to arrive in Indigenous homelands at the turn of the eighteenth century, these small nations, or petites nations as the French called them, pulled colonists into their political and social systems, thereby steering the development of early Louisiana. In some cases, the same practices that helped Native peoples withstand colonization in the eighteenth century, including frequent migration, living alongside foreign nations, and welcoming outsiders into their lands, have made it difficult for their contemporary descendants to achieve federal acknowledgment and full rights as Native American peoples.The Great Power of Small Nations tackles questions of Native power past and present and provides a fresh examination of the formidable and resilient Native nations who helped shape the modern Gulf South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aIndians of North AmericazGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazGulf Coast (U.S.)xPolitics and government. 0aIndians of North AmericazMississippi River ValleyxHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazMississippi River ValleyxPolitics and government. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aChoctaws.  aFrench Empire.  aHoumas.  aIndigenous Studies.  aLouisiana.  aNatchez War.  aNative Americans.  aPeoria.  aPetites Nations.  aTunicas.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://www.degruyter.co